"Alter T., Appel B., Bartelt E., Dieckmann R., Eichhorn C., Erler R., Frank C., Gerdts G., Gunzer F., Hühn S., Neifer J., Oberheitmann B., Strauch E.","Vibrio infections from food and sea water: Introducing the ""vibrioNet"" [Vibrio-Infektionen durch Lebensmittel und Meerwasser: Das Netzwerk .,VibrioNet"" stellt sich vor]",2011,"Bundesgesundheitsblatt - Gesundheitsforschung - Gesundheitsschutz","54","11",,"1235","1240",,,10.1007/s00103-011-1359-1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-81855220968&partnerID=40&md5=8b3c7abc9fa0707e857320af077c7eec","Institut für Lebensmittelhygiene, Freie Universität Berlin, Berlin, Germany; Bundesinstitut für Risikobewertung, Diedersdorfer Weg 1, Berlin 12277, Germany; Institut für Fische und Fischereierzeugnisse, LAVES, Cuxhaven, Germany; Institut für Medizinische Mikrobiologie und Hygiene, Technische Universität Dresden, Dresden, Germany; Alfred Wegener Institut für Polar- und Meeresforschung, Helgoland, Germany; Robert Koch-Institut, Berlin, Germany; Q-Bioanalytic GmbH, Bremerhaven, Germany","Alter, T., Institut für Lebensmittelhygiene, Freie Universität Berlin, Berlin, Germany; Appel, B., Bundesinstitut für Risikobewertung, Diedersdorfer Weg 1, Berlin 12277, Germany; Bartelt, E., Institut für Fische und Fischereierzeugnisse, LAVES, Cuxhaven, Germany; Dieckmann, R., Bundesinstitut für Risikobewertung, Diedersdorfer Weg 1, Berlin 12277, Germany; Eichhorn, C., Institut für Medizinische Mikrobiologie und Hygiene, Technische Universität Dresden, Dresden, Germany; Erler, R., Alfred Wegener Institut für Polar- und Meeresforschung, Helgoland, Germany; Frank, C., Robert Koch-Institut, Berlin, Germany; Gerdts, G., Alfred Wegener Institut für Polar- und Meeresforschung, Helgoland, Germany; Gunzer, F., Institut für Medizinische Mikrobiologie und Hygiene, Technische Universität Dresden, Dresden, Germany; Hühn, S., Institut für Lebensmittelhygiene, Freie Universität Berlin, Berlin, Germany; Neifer, J., Robert Koch-Institut, Berlin, Germany; Oberheitmann, B., Q-Bioanalytic GmbH, Bremerhaven, Germany; Strauch, E., Bundesinstitut für Risikobewertung, Diedersdorfer Weg 1, Berlin 12277, Germany","Vibrio is a genus of bacteria present in surface and coastal waters as well as in marine organisms worldwide. In many countries, pathogenic Vibrio species are a main cause of bacterial diarrhea, which may result from comsumption of contaminated seafood and fish products or from drinking contaminated water. Vibrio infections may also gain in importance in our regions due to global warming and the increase in the world trade of seafood. The research network ""VibrioNet"" studies pathogenic Vibrios in the marine environment and in seafood consumed by humans as a potential, new emerging zoonotic agent. An assessment of the risk arising from pathogenic non-cholera-vibrios in central Europe is the target of a multidisciplinary research effort. The research network will be strengthened by cooperations with international partners from countries in which Vibrio infections play a major role (Bangladesh, Chile, India, Thailand, and Vietnam). © 2011 Springer Medizin Verlag.","Food; Seawater; Vibrio; VibrioNet","sea water; animal; article; climate change; cross-sectional study; developing country; diarrhea; disease transmission; Europe; food poisoning; human; international cooperation; microbiology; sea food; sepsis; statistics; vibriosis; wound infection; zoonosis; Animals; Climate Change; Cross-Sectional Studies; Developing Countries; Diarrhea; Europe; Fish Products; Foodborne Diseases; Humans; International Agencies; Seafood; Seawater; Sepsis; Vibrio Infections; Water Microbiology; Wound Infection; Zoonoses",,,,,,"Wiltshire, K.H., Manly, B.F.J., The warming trend at Helgoland Roads, North Sea: Phytoplankton response (2004) Helgoland Marine Research, 58 (4), pp. 269-273. , DOI 10.1007/s10152-004-0196-0; Paz, S., Bisharat, N., Paz, E., Kidar, O., Cohen, D., Climate change and the emergence of Vibrio vulnificus disea